 >> On Thu, Dec 24, 2015 at 8:12 PM,  <leif@leifandersen.net> wrote:
 >>> A new problem report is waiting at
 >>>   http://bugs.racket-lang.org/query/?cmd=view&pr=15207
 >>>
 >>> Reported by Leif Andersen for release: 6.3.0.8--2015-12-19(-/f)
 >>>
 >>> *** Description:
 >>> It seems like DrRacket continues to run a program that uses places even after the stop button is pressed.
 >>>
 >>> I'm not sure if this is a bug, or just a usability bug. But either way, it seems like there should be a way (in the GUI, either the stop button directly or a button right next to it) to stop all of the running places.
 >>>
 >>> *** How to repeat:
 >>> 1. In a new file, create the following program:
 >>>
 >>> #lang racket
 >>>
 >>> (list
 >>>  (thread
 >>>   (lambda ()
 >>>     (future (lambda ()
 >>>               (let loop () (loop))))))
 >>>  (thread
 >>>   (lambda ()
 >>>     (future (lambda ()
 >>>               (let loop () (loop))))))
 >>>  (thread
 >>>   (lambda ()
 >>>     (future (lambda ()
 >>>               (let loop () (loop))))))
 >>>  (thread
 >>>   (lambda ()
 >>>     (future (lambda ()
 >>>               (let loop () (loop)))))))
 >>>
 >>> (let loop () (loop))
 >>>
 >>> 2. Hit run
 >>> 2a. Notice in `top -o cpu` that DrRacket is now taking about 500% CPU.
 >>>
 >>> 3. Click stop.
 >>> 3a. Not again in top that DrRacket is now at 400% cpu. I suspect this is because the main thread has stopped, but the other ones have not.
 >>>
 >>> *** Environment:
 >>> macosx "Darwin FATT.local 14.5.0 Darwin Kernel Version 14.5.0: Wed Jul 29 02:26:53 PDT 2015; root:xnu-2782.40.9~1/RELEASE_X86_64 x86_64" (x86_64-macosx/3m) (get-display-depth) = 32
